<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-04T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-04T08:00:00-05:00" n="316" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3787: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-04T14:00:00+01:00">June 4, 1934—2
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 4—12:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>132. Consulate’s No. 129, June 2,6 p.m., paragraph 2c, arms embargo
                                proposal. In addition to the states in its 1933 reply Italy has
                                formally named Soviet Russia and Japan. Question of communicating
                                with those Governments is not yet settled.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>